d to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Phillip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Philip  , in part a reflection of the surname, which is usually spelled <i>Phillips</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Phillip ap Llewelyn was born about 1222, in Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Llewelyn Fraisg ap Hywel, was 79 and his mother, Lleuci Ferch Y Golwg, was 74. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"ABT 1222–":"umbes 1222–Surnud","1222–Male":"1222–Surnud","1248–Male":"1248–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1150–Female":"1150–Surnud","1248":"1248","ABT 1222":"umbes 1222","1145":"1145","1222":"1222","1150":"1150","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Elston, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Elston, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1222–":"noin 1222–Kuollut","1222–Male":"1222–Kuollut","1248–Male":"1248–Kuollut","1145–Male":"1145–Kuollut","1150–Female":"1150–Kuollut","1248":"1248","ABT 1222":"noin 1222","1145":"1145","1222":"1222","1150":"1150","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Elston, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Elston, Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"ABT 1222–":"environ 1222–Décédé","1222–Male":"1222–Décédé","1248–Male":"1248–Décédé","1145–Male":"1145–Décédé","1150–Female":"1150–Décédée","1248":"1248","ABT 1222":"environ 1222","1145":"1145","1222":"1222","1150":"1150","Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, England":"Wolverton, Buckinghamshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Un